"""
MKT Context Layer — Ezekiel chapters 11–14
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-ezekiel-11-14-fill.py

Historical-cultural contexts:

Ch 11: Final scene of the temple vision (chs 8-11). Jerusalem's pro-Egyptian
  leaders assert the "pot/meat" theology of invulnerability. The glory of YHWH
  departs from the city to the Mount of Olives — the most theologically
  catastrophic event in OT history. YHWH promises to be a "little sanctuary"
  for exiles, previewing synagogue/diaspora theology.

Ch 12: Two sign acts performed in Babylon representing Jerusalem's fall:
  (1) exile-baggage mime (Zedekiah's night flight, capture, blinding);
  (2) trembling-eating mime (siege terror). Two popular proverbs dismissing
  Ezekiel's urgency — "the days drag on" and "the vision is for the distant
  future" — both rebuffed.

Ch 13: Against unauthorized prophets who cry "Peace" over a whitewashed wall
  (the tapel/whitewash metaphor); against prophetesses using Babylonian-style
  magic arm-bands and veils in the exilic community.

Ch 14: Elders with "idols in their hearts" consult Ezekiel; YHWH refuses
  syncretistic consultation. The Noah/Daniel/Job triad of ancient righteous
  men — only their own lives saved by their righteousness in a doomed land.
  The Daniel is likely the ancient Canaanite Dan'el of the Aqhat epic, not
  the biblical Daniel. Four devastating judgments on Jerusalem.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZK_CTX = {
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>The Spirit transports Ezekiel to the east gate of the temple complex — the principal gate through which the glory of YHWH will soon depart. Twenty-five men are present, including Jaazaniah son of Azzur and Pelatiah son of Benaiah, named as community leaders. This Jaazaniah differs from the one in 8:11 (son of Shaphan, the scribe's family): a different influential man, representing the political-priestly establishment that shaped Jerusalem's pro-Egyptian foreign policy under Zedekiah.</p>",
    "2": "<p>YHWH identifies these leaders as those 'who plan harm and give wicked counsel in this city' — the political elite who were advising continued resistance to Babylon and alliance with Egypt. Zedekiah's court was divided between pro-Babylonian and pro-Egyptian factions; the men here represent the latter, whose advice ultimately led to Jerusalem's destruction when Pharaoh Hophra's attempted military intervention failed (Jer 37:5-8).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The 'pot/caldron' proverb: 'the time of judgment is not coming soon; let us build houses — this city is the caldron and we are the meat' (or: 'is it not soon to build houses? This city is the caldron and we are the flesh'). The proverb is ambiguous: it may be a claim of security ('we are safe inside the city like meat in a pot') or a defiant challenge ('we are being cooked already — let's build for the future'). Either way, the leaders are dismissing Ezekiel's warnings of imminent destruction and counseling normalcy and permanence in Jerusalem.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The prophetic commission to speak against the 25 leaders is urgent — the double imperative 'prophesy, son of man!' underscores the immediacy. The formula addresses both the leaders in the vision and, by extension, the exilic community in Babylon who needs to hear YHWH's verdict on Jerusalem's political decisions. Ezekiel's prophecy in Babylon judges events happening in Jerusalem.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Spirit of YHWH descending on Ezekiel at the moment of prophesying is the standard inspiration formula — the same Spirit that lifted Ezekiel in transportation now empowers the prophetic word. The content is direct accusation: 'That is what you have been saying, house of Israel' — YHWH directly challenges the leaders' internal deliberations, demonstrating knowledge of their private counsel. For a culture where the gods were believed to be accessible to those with proper rituals, the claim that YHWH hears internal deliberation is pointed.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'You have multiplied your slain in this city and filled its streets with the dead' — the charge of judicial murder, the shedding of innocent blood, which was the legal basis for land defilement (Num 35:33). Jerusalem's streets filled with the dead refers to the same situation as 9:9 — the violence and injustice that Ezekiel's temple tour revealed as the causes of the glory's departure. The leaders' political decisions have resulted in deaths.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The 'pot' proverb is reinterpreted against the leaders: those who have been killed in the city are the 'meat' in the caldron; the living leaders will be removed from it and judged. The irony reverses their claim to safety: the 'meat' that the pot preserves is the slain — those they killed. The leaders who used the proverb to claim protection are expelled from it. YHWH turns their own theological analogy against them.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'You feared the sword, and I will bring the sword upon you': the feared thing becomes the actual outcome — a principle of prophetic judgment throughout the OT (cf. Job 3:25 'what I feared has come upon me'). The leaders' policy was driven by fear of the Babylonian sword; YHWH declares that this fear will be precisely fulfilled through their own decisions. The Babylonian sword that they are trying to avoid through political maneuvering is the one YHWH will bring through their political maneuvering.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'I will bring you out of it and hand you over to foreigners': the expulsion from Jerusalem (the 'pot' they claimed as protection) to the judgment administered by foreigners (the Babylonians). The cultural context: being handed over to foreign judgment was an extreme disgrace in the ancient Near East, where rulers expected to be judged only by their peers or superior powers in the divine hierarchy. Being given to 'zarim' (foreigners/strangers) was social death before physical death.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'I will judge you at the border of Israel': historical fulfillment — Nebuchadnezzar executed Zedekiah's sons at Riblah (in Syria, on the Orontes River, near the northern border of the land claimed by Israel), then blinded Zedekiah there before taking him to Babylon (2 Kgs 25:6-7). Riblah was Nebuchadnezzar's military headquarters during the siege of Jerusalem. The phrase 'you will know that I am the LORD' closes the judgment announcement with the recognition formula — even in judgment, YHWH's identity is the goal.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The direct rebuttal of the pot-proverb: 'This city will not be your caldron, nor will you be the flesh inside it; I will judge you at the border of Israel.' The proverb promised protection inside Jerusalem; the judgment will be outside Jerusalem. The spatial reversal dismantles the entire proverb structure. The theological claim underlying it — that Jerusalem's walls provide divine protection — is explicitly falsified.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The grounds of judgment: 'for you have not walked in my statutes or carried out my judgments; you have acted according to the standards of the nations around you.' The nations' standards (mishpetei haggoyim) — the political, ethical, and religious practices of Babylon, Egypt, and the surrounding peoples — are the alternative to YHWH's statutes that Jerusalem has chosen. The covenant defined Israel as a nation apart from the nations; choosing the nations' standards over YHWH's is covenant suicide.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Pelatiah son of Benaiah dies during the vision — the only recorded death during a prophetic vision in the OT. The name Pelatiah ('YHWH saves/rescues') is bitterly ironic: the man named after YHWH's saving action dies as Ezekiel pronounces judgment. Ezekiel's dismayed cry ('Ah, Lord GOD, will you make a complete end of the remnant of Israel?') shows the prophet's horror that the judgment vision is lethal even to those only seen in vision. The death is a sign confirming the oracle's authority.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The word-event formula introduces a new divine speech within the vision — the turn from judgment to promise. The transition from judgment-oracle (vv.1-13) to restoration-promise (vv.14-21) follows the standard Ezekielian pattern: the announcement of punishment is followed immediately by the announcement of the covenant future. The two movements are inseparable: the same God who judges also restores.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Your brothers — your own kinsmen — and all the house of Israel, those the inhabitants of Jerusalem have said of: Go far from the LORD; the land has been given to us as a possession.' This verse documents the actual social conflict between the exilic community (Jehoiachin's deportees, 597 BCE) and the Jerusalem remnant. The Jerusalem residents have theologically dismissed the exiles ('go far from the LORD') while claiming the land for themselves. They are interpreting the 597 deportation as divine rejection of the exiles and divine favor toward themselves.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Although I sent them far away among the nations and scattered them among the countries, I have been a sanctuary for them for a little while in the countries where they have gone.' The phrase <em>miqdash me'at</em> ('little/lesser sanctuary') is theologically revolutionary: YHWH can be a sanctuary presence for his people outside the land, without the temple, among the foreign nations. This is the scriptural foundation for diaspora Judaism and the synagogue as a place of divine encounter. The temple is not the only possible place of YHWH's presence; exile does not mean divine abandonment.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The first restoration promise within the temple vision: the gathering from the nations and return to the land of Israel (a second Exodus). The promise is given while Ezekiel is still in the temple vision context — connecting the departure of YHWH's glory with the future return of the people. The departure of the Shekinah from the temple does not mean the end of YHWH's purposes for Israel; it initiates the exile that will end in restoration.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'When they come there, they will remove all its detestable things and all its abominations' — the spiritual purification of the land as part of the return. The same abominations and detestable things that Ezekiel's temple tour revealed in chs 8-9 (idol worship in the temple precincts) will be removed by the restored community. The exile functionally purges both the people (through suffering and transformation) and the land (through their absence from it).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The earlier form of the new heart promise (the fuller version in 36:26-27): 'I will give them one heart and put a new spirit within them; I will remove the heart of stone from their flesh and give them a heart of flesh.' The corporate unity ('one heart' — echad) addresses the divided counsels and multiple loyalties of the Judean community. The heart of stone (<em>lev ha'avanim</em>) was the hardened, unresponsive heart that could not hear YHWH; the heart of flesh (<em>lev basar</em>) is a responsive, living heart capable of covenant fidelity.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The covenant formula applied to the restored community: 'then they will walk in my statutes, keep my ordinances, and obey them; they will be my people, and I will be their God.' The same covenant formula that ch 12 cited as the thing the leaders had violated is here promised as what the restored community will fulfill — but now through the divinely given new heart, not through human moral effort. The covenant is restored not by Israel's improved performance but by YHWH's interior transformation of Israel.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'But as for those whose hearts pursue their detestable idols and abominations, I will bring their deeds down on their own heads': the contrast with vv.19-20. The new heart is given to the gathered exiles; those who persist in idolatry receive the recompense of their deeds. The election language of the restoration section is not universalist: some in Israel receive the new heart by YHWH's sovereign gift; others persist in idolatry and receive judgment.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The cherubim spread their wings and the chariot-throne complex moves eastward — the glory is leaving the temple precincts. The gradual departure: from above the cherubim (10:1-2), to the threshold of the temple (10:4), to the east gate (10:18-19), and now moving further. The cherubim's wings are spread — the posture of movement and departure, as opposed to the hovering position of presence.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'The glory of the LORD ascended from within the city and stood on the mountain to the east of the city' — the Mount of Olives. The Shekinah glory that had resided in the temple since Solomon's dedication (1 Kgs 8:10-11) has now fully departed from the city. It pauses on the Mount of Olives — perhaps a final position before ultimate withdrawal. This mountain to the east of Jerusalem will become significant in later tradition: Zechariah 14:4 (YHWH's feet will stand on the Mount of Olives), and the New Testament placement of Jesus's Olivet Discourse and ascension at the same location.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Ezekiel is returned by the Spirit to Chaldea — the vision journey is complete. The transportation formula closes the vision of chs 8-11, the longest and most complex vision unit in the book: vision (ch 8-9) → theophany and glory departure (ch 10) → judgment and restoration promises (ch 11). The return to Chaldea/Babylon is the standard closing of an Ezekielian vision-transport (cf. 3:12-15; 43:1-5).</p>",
    "25": "<p>'I told the exiles everything the LORD had shown me' — the prophetic disclosure is for the community. The vision of the temple's corruption, the glory's departure, the judgment on Jerusalem's leaders, and the restoration promises are all disclosed to the Babylonian exilic community. The exiles in Babylon are the primary audience for Ezekiel's message about events in Jerusalem. They need to know both why the city will fall (the vision) and what YHWH promises afterward (the restoration oracle).</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>New oracle unit with the standard word-event formula. Chapters 12-19 form a section of disputations and sign acts that respond to popular objections to Ezekiel's message. Ch 12 addresses the charge that the coming judgment is remote or will not happen.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'You live among a rebellious people who have eyes but do not see, who have ears but do not hear' — the blindness/deafness formula echoes Isa 6:9-10 (the judicial hardening of Israel) and Deut 29:4 (Israel throughout the wilderness period lacking eyes to see and ears to hear). The exilic community, despite having witnessed the 597 deportation, refuses to interpret it as Ezekiel urges. They remain <em>beit hameri</em> (rebellious house) — the distinctive Ezekielian phrase for Israel's persistent covenant defiance.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The exile-baggage sign act: Ezekiel is to prepare deportation equipment by day in full view of the community, then move from his place to another location. The act must be visible and public — <em>le'eineihem</em> ('in their sight/before their eyes') appears repeatedly in vv. 3-7. The sign act exploits the theatrical potential of prophecy: what cannot be heard as words might be seen as action. 'Perhaps they will understand, though they are a rebellious house': even a reluctant prophetic hope that visual demonstration will reach those words cannot.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The day/evening sequence of the sign act: bring out baggage by day (visible to all); go out in the evening as if for exile. The two-phase timing adds temporal drama. In ancient military contexts, conquered populations were typically organized for deportation marches during daylight; the cover of night suggests secretive flight rather than organized deportation — already implying the flight of the leadership rather than general deportation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Dig through the wall in their sight and carry your things out through it' — the act mimics digging through the mud-brick wall of a house to escape under cover of darkness. The gesture is historically precise: 2 Kings 25:4 records that Zedekiah and his men 'broke through the city wall' at night and fled. The prophetic sign act in Babylon anticipates the literal act in Jerusalem with remarkable specificity.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Carry it out on your shoulder at dusk; cover your face so that you cannot see the land' — two separate actions, each with specific significance: shoulder-carrying (the mode of a humiliated captive lacking wagons or animals) and face-covering (mourning posture; also mimics Zedekiah's blinding — he will not see Babylon with his eyes, v.13). 'I have made you a sign to the house of Israel' — the prophet as embodied sign, his own body the text to be read.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The execution report confirms the sign act was performed exactly as commanded: baggage brought out by day, wall dug through by hand in the evening, things carried out on shoulder at dusk. The precision of the execution report serves both to validate the prophetic obedience and to ensure the symbolic correspondence between the sign act and the coming event. Ezekiel's body and actions are the medium of prophecy when words are dismissed.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The morning enquiry: YHWH asks for the interpretation to be given after the act has been observed. The sequence — act first, then meaning — reverses the normal order of prophetic sign acts (which might be explained before or during). Here the act provokes a question, and the question receives the interpretation. This is pedagogically intentional: the community must engage with the visual symbol before receiving the verbal explanation.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The question attributed to the watching community ('What are you doing?') is the interpretive trigger. The act has produced the desired curiosity — even from a 'rebellious house.' The question demonstrates that the sign act succeeded in its communicative purpose: those who would not hear words were drawn to ask about the visible action. The body of the prophet as prophetic text is legible in a way that verbal prophecy alone is not.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'This oracle concerns the prince in Jerusalem and all the house of Israel in it' — the sign act's referent is identified: the prince (<em>nasi</em>) is Zedekiah, the last king of Judah (Ezekiel characteristically uses <em>nasi</em> rather than <em>melek</em> for Judah's kings after the exile of Jehoiachin). The 'house of Israel' refers to the population of Jerusalem who will suffer the same fate as the prince. The oracle bridges the exilic community in Babylon (watching the sign act) and the Jerusalem community (who will experience its fulfillment).</p>",
    "11": "<p>'I am your sign. As I have done, so shall it be done to them' — the prophet as living analogy. Ezekiel's actions are not merely symbolic but causally connected to the coming events: the sign act participates in the reality it represents (a form of prophetic performative speech). 'They will be uprooted and go into exile': <em>galut yiglu</em> (H1540, to go into exile) — the vocabulary of forced deportation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'The prince among them will carry his things on his shoulder in the dark and go out; they will dig through the wall to bring things out' — the prince's flight matches the sign act precisely. The darkened escape, the carrying of possessions (no horses or wagons for stealth), the hole dug through the wall — all realized in Zedekiah's 587 flight (2 Kgs 25:4). The face-covering: either for concealment (night flight) or as prophetic sign of impending blindness.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'I will spread my net over him and catch him in my snare; I will bring him to Babylon, to the land of the Chaldeans, though he will not see it, and he will die there' — the three-part prediction fulfilled exactly in 2 Kings 25:5-7: (1) Zedekiah caught near Jericho (the net/snare); (2) brought to Riblah (not yet Babylon) where his sons were executed; (3) his eyes put out and he was taken to Babylon in chains — seeing neither his homeland again nor, apparently, Babylon itself before death. The blindness — 'will not see it' — is the key specific detail that marks this as authentic pre-event prophecy.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'I will scatter to every wind all his supporters and all his troops': the dispersal of Zedekiah's military forces is historically recorded in the capture of the officers at Riblah and the flight of the remaining soldiers in various directions (2 Kgs 25:4-5). The winds as the instrument of dispersal — a cosmic image for the irreversible, multi-directional scattering of a defeated army.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The recognition formula applied to the diaspora itself: 'they will know that I am the LORD when I scatter them among the nations and disperse them throughout the countries.' The exile that appears to demonstrate YHWH's powerlessness actually demonstrates his sovereignty — he is the one who scattered them. YHWH claiming agency over Israel's defeat and exile is the central theological claim of Ezekiel's message: the exile is not evidence against YHWH but evidence of YHWH's covenant-keeping fidelity.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'But I will spare a small number of them from sword, famine, and plague, so that they may confess all their abominations among the nations where they go' — the preserved remnant's function is testimony. The survivors do not survive because of merit but for a missional purpose: to confess (<em>saphar</em>, narrate/declare) Israel's abominations to the nations. The exile community becomes an involuntary witness to the nations about YHWH's justice. 'Then they will know that I am the LORD' — the nations' knowledge of YHWH comes through observing Israel's history of judgment and confession.</p>",
    "17": "<p>New oracle unit introduces the second sign act of the chapter — the trembling-eating mime. The word-event formula marks a new divine speech, distinct from the exile-baggage sign act of vv.1-16. The two sign acts together (exile mime + anxiety mime) represent the two dimensions of Jerusalem's coming fate: deportation and the terror of the siege period that precedes it.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Son of man, eat your bread with trembling and drink your water with shaking and dread' — the prophet's body again as the prophetic text. Trembling (<em>reada</em>, H7461, quaking/trembling) and shaking and dread (<em>deavon</em>, H1674, anxiety/care) while eating and drinking: the most basic human acts of sustenance performed in terror. The sign represents the psychological and physical state of Jerusalem's inhabitants during the siege.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Say to the people of the land: This is what the Lord GOD says about the inhabitants of Jerusalem in the land of Israel' — the sign act is explicitly about the situation in the land, not in Babylon. 'They will eat their bread in dread and drink their water in horror, for their land will be stripped of everything in it because of the violence of all who live there' — the siege conditions: food eaten in terror, the land stripped bare. The violence (<em>chamas</em>, H2555, violence/brutality) of Jerusalem's inhabitants is the cause of the very siege violence they will experience.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'The inhabited cities will be laid waste and the land made desolate; then you will know that I am the LORD' — the comprehensive desolation oracle closes the trembling-eating section. The specific prediction: 'inhabited cities' becoming waste is remarkable from a Babylonian exile context — the Babylonian practice was not to leave cities completely empty but to install a rump administration (which they did with Gedaliah, 2 Kgs 25:22). The theological point is emphatic: the visible flourishing of Jerusalem as a city will end.</p>",
    "21": "<p>New oracle unit (third in ch 12) introduced by word-event formula. The two proverbs that follow (vv.22, 27) represent real popular theological responses to Ezekiel's message in the exilic community. Ezekiel directly quotes and refutes these sayings.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'What is this proverb you keep hearing in the land of Israel: The days drag on and every vision fails?' — the first dismissal proverb. The exilic community has been hearing prophetic messages of doom for years — from Jeremiah before the exile, from Ezekiel in Babylon. Nothing has happened (yet) to Jerusalem. The proverb reflects rational frustration with unfulfilled prophecy and the natural human tendency to dismiss warnings that do not immediately materialize. 'The days drag on' (<em>ya'arku hayyamim</em>) — time passing becomes an argument against prophetic urgency.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'I will put an end to this proverb; it will no longer be used in Israel' — YHWH's refutation is not a counter-argument but an announcement: the proverb will be falsified by events. 'But say to them: The days are near and every vision fulfilled' — the reversal of the proverb. The same 'days' that were dragging on without fulfillment are 'near' (<em>qarov</em>, H7138, near/at hand); the visions that were 'failing' are about to be 'fulfilled' (<em>dabar</em>, the fulfillment of a word). The counter-proverb will replace the dismissal proverb.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'For there will be no more empty visions or flattering divination within the house of Israel' — <em>chazon shaw</em> (false/vain vision) and <em>qesem chalaq</em> (flattering divination) — the categories of false prophecy. The authentic words of YHWH through Ezekiel will replace the pleasant-sounding false prophecy that had reassured Jerusalem. The 'flattering divination' (<em>chalaq</em>, H2509, smooth/slippery/flattering) is the same word used for the smooth words that replace honest speech (cf. Ps 12:2-3; Isa 30:10 'tell us pleasant things').</p>",
    "25": "<p>'For I am the LORD; I will speak, and what I speak will happen — it will not be delayed any further' — YHWH's self-identification grounds the reliability of his word. The contrast with false prophecy: the false prophets speak smooth words that comfort but do not happen; YHWH speaks words that may not comfort but will happen. 'In your days, O rebellious house, I will speak a word and perform it' — the urgency is temporal: the fulfillment is coming within the current generation.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The second dismissal proverb is introduced with another word-event formula — it is a distinct piece of public opinion that Ezekiel is commanded to address. The word-event formula's repetition in vv.21, 26 marks the systematic character of Ezekiel's engagement with popular counter-messages.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'The house of Israel is saying, the vision he sees is for the distant future, and he prophesies about times far off' — the second strategy for dismissing Ezekiel: conceding that he might be a genuine prophet but whose message concerns a future so remote as to be irrelevant to the current generation. This is the strategy of admitting prophetic validity while draining it of urgency. Ezekiel's message is acknowledged but quarantined in an irrelevant eschatological future.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'None of my words will be put off any longer — what I speak will be done, declares the Lord GOD' — the flat refusal of the 'distant future' proverb. YHWH's words are not deferred to a comfortable future but are happening now. The chapter ends with the unqualified assertion of prophetic immediacy: the coming events are not theoretical or future — they are imminent. This counter to both proverbs establishes the theological platform for the false-prophet oracles that follow in ch 13.</p>"
  },
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>The word-event formula opens a new major section: the oracle against false prophets (vv.1-16) and prophetesses (vv.17-23). The conflict between true and false prophecy is one of the central crises of the pre-exilic and exilic periods (cf. 1 Kgs 22; Jer 23:9-40; 27-28; Mic 3:5-12). Ezekiel's oracle addresses the specific false prophets operating in the exilic community and in Jerusalem who were contradicting his message of judgment.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Prophesy against the prophets of Israel who are prophesying' — the doubled verb creates emphasis. Ezekiel as the prophet sent against the prophets is a distinctive Ezekielian role (cf. 2:5-7 where the rebellious house defines the audience). 'Say to those who prophesy out of their own hearts (<em>miLibbam</em>): Hear the word of the LORD' — the false prophets 'prophesy from their own hearts': their messages originate in human desire, fear, or political alignment rather than divine commission. The contrast with Ezekiel is total: his messages are received despite being personally unwelcome.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Woe to the foolish prophets who follow their own spirit and have seen nothing' — <em>woe</em> (<em>hoy</em>, H1945, the funeral lament turned into judgment oracle) applied to prophets who claim to follow the divine Spirit but are actually following their own spirit (<em>rucham</em>). 'Have seen nothing' (<em>velo ra'u</em>) — in the context of prophetic authorization, the fundamental qualification is to have seen the divine council or received a genuine vision (cf. 1 Kgs 22:19-22; Jer 23:18). These prophets have no visionary authorization.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Your prophets are like foxes among ruins, O Israel' — the foxes/jackals that inhabit ruins: scavengers in desolated buildings, not defenders of intact structures. The metaphor is precise: the false prophets are like animals that thrive in the aftermath of destruction rather than preventing it. They occupy the ruins of whatever their failed prophecies create, profiting from breakdown rather than preventing it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'You have not gone up into the breaches or built up the wall for the house of Israel to stand in battle on the day of the LORD' — the military metaphor of defensive theology. The true prophet stands in the gap (<em>peretz</em>, H6556, breach/gap) where the wall is broken — interceding, warning, calling to repentance. Moses 'stood in the breach' (Ps 106:23) to prevent YHWH's destroying Israel in the golden-calf incident. The false prophets have abandoned the breach while claiming to be Israel's spiritual defenders.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'They see false visions and utter lying divinations, saying the LORD declares — but the LORD has not sent them; yet they expect their word to be confirmed' — the false prophet's professional stance: claiming YHWH's authorization while awaiting event-confirmation of their own words. The hope that circumstances will validate the prophecy ('they expect their word to be confirmed') is the opposite of the authentic prophet's position, who announces what is revealed regardless of whether it will be received.</p>",
    "7": "<p>YHWH directly challenges the false prophets: 'Have you not seen a false vision and spoken a lying divination when you say the LORD declares, even though I have not spoken?' — the rhetorical question exposes the false prophets' claim. The repetition of <em>ne'um YHWH</em> ('the LORD declares') as a false claim is an abuse of the most authoritative formula in prophetic speech. Claiming YHWH's speech-act for human words is the paradigmatic prophetic sin.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'I am against you, declares the Lord GOD' — the <em>hineni elecha</em> formula directed at the false prophets as divine adversary. The same formula used against Tyre (26:3), Sidon (28:22), and Egypt (29:3) is now deployed against Israel's own prophets. Being the target of YHWH's <em>hineni elecha</em> is as serious a judgment as any foreign nation receives in the OAN section.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'My hand will be against the prophets who see false visions and divine lies; they will not be in the council of my people, nor be recorded in the records of the house of Israel, nor enter the land of Israel; then you will know that I am the Lord GOD' — the three-part exclusion: (1) from the assembly (<em>sod ami</em>, H5475 + H5971 — the intimate council of the people, the community's deliberative body); (2) from the written records of Israel (the community's genealogical registers determining membership and land rights); (3) from the land itself. The three exclusions are progressive in permanence. The land exclusion applies to both the pre-exile and restoration contexts.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Because they have led my people astray, saying Peace when there is no peace — and when someone builds a flimsy wall, they plaster it with whitewash' — the double crime: the message ('peace, peace' — the same phrase in Jer 6:14; 8:11 as the signature of false prophecy) and the concealment (whitewash on a weak wall). The 'flimsy wall' (<em>chayitz</em>, H2434, the weak partition or wall) represents the political-theological structure the false prophets are supporting: Zedekiah's rebellion against Babylon, the alliance with Egypt, the belief that Jerusalem would stand.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Say to those who plaster with whitewash that it will fall — a flooding rain will come, great hailstones will fall, and a violent wind will burst out' — the three instruments of the wall's destruction are both literal (the forces of nature) and metaphorical (the Babylonian siege, which involved engineering operations against Jerusalem's walls including earthworks and battering rams). The flooding rain, hailstones, and stormy wind are the instruments of YHWH's theophanic judgment (cf. Ezek 38:22; Job 38:22-23).</p>",
    "12": "<p>'When the wall falls, will it not be said to you: Where is the plaster you covered it with?' — the rhetorical humiliation of the false prophets after the event. The question is anticipated: when the wall that the false prophets declared safe collapses in the Babylonian assault, the community will demand an accounting. The false prophet's inability to answer the post-disaster question of 'where is your whitewash?' is the final exposure of the original fraud.</p>",
    "13": "<p>YHWH's own instruments of judgment: stormy wind, flooding rain in wrath, great hailstones in consuming fury. The divine weather-instruments are specifically directed at the wall and those who whitewashed it. The theological point: it is YHWH who tears down the false-prophet-supported wall, not merely natural forces or Babylonian military power. The Babylonian siege is the human instrument; YHWH is the divine causation.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'I will tear down the wall you plastered with whitewash and bring it to the ground, so that its foundation is laid bare; when it falls, you will perish within it, and you will know that I am the LORD' — the prophets who whitewashed the wall will be inside it when it falls. The false prophets who assured Jerusalem of its security will be present for its fall, experiencing the consequence of their own fraud. The 'foundation laid bare' is a construction image: a collapsed wall exposes its inadequate foundation, which is what caused the failure.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'So I will spend my wrath on the wall and on those who plastered it, and I will declare: The wall is gone and so are those who plastered it — the prophets of Israel who prophesied about Jerusalem and saw visions of peace for her when there was no peace' — the final epitaph of the false prophets. The wall and the whitewashers perish together. The characterization 'prophesied concerning Jerusalem and saw visions of peace for her' is the permanent summary of false prophecy's content: location-specific and peace-assuring. All false prophecy about Jerusalem in this period shared this character.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The closing summary of the false-prophet oracle: these prophets who saw shalom-visions for Jerusalem while YHWH declared no shalom. The contrast between the false prophets' message and YHWH's message (through Ezekiel) is total: they say shalom, YHWH says catastrophe; they are inside the city assuring its safety, YHWH is in Babylon declaring its fall. The community must choose whose word to trust.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Son of man, set your face against the daughters of your people who prophesy out of their own hearts': the second oracle targets prophetesses. Female prophets are attested in Israel (Miriam, Deborah, Huldah) but these women are explicitly unauthorized: 'out of their own hearts' is the same accusation as the male false prophets. The transition from male prophets to female prophetesses is structural: Ezekiel is comprehensive in his criticism of all illegitimate spiritual authority in the community.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'Woe to the women who sew magic bands on all wrists and make veils for heads of every height, to hunt souls' — the magic bands (<em>kesatot</em>, H3704, a hapax legomenon; some connect to Akkadian <em>kisu</em>, a pouch used in Babylonian magic) and veils used in magical practices. The 'hunting of souls' (<em>tzeyd nephashoth</em>) — the practitioners are using ritual objects to capture or bind the psychic vitality of clients or targets. Babylonian magical texts (including the Maqlu and Shurpu series) describe similar binding rituals using bands and head-coverings.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'You have profaned me among my people for handfuls of barley and pieces of bread' — the prophets (v.19 addresses them as 'you') are desacralizing YHWH's name for trivial material gain. The fees: 'handfuls of barley and pieces of bread' — the most basic subsistence food, suggesting that the prophetesses' clients are from the lower economic stratum of the exilic community. The cheapness of the fee underscores the cheapness of the spiritual transaction: YHWH's holiness traded for barley.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'I am against your magic bands with which you hunt lives like birds; I will tear them from your arms and set free the lives you hunt like birds' — the imagery shifts from wall-construction (male prophets) to bird-hunting (female prophetesses). The magic bands are the traps and nets used to hunt birds; YHWH tearing the bands from the prophetesses' arms is the act of liberating those they have trapped. The freed 'birds' are the people who had been spiritually bound by the false religious practices.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'I will also tear off your veils and deliver my people from your grip; they will no longer be prey in your hands, and you will know that I am the LORD' — the liberation of the exilic community from false spiritual authority. The 'grip' or hand of the prophetesses is contrasted with YHWH's hand: YHWH's hand (<em>yad YHWH</em>) brings the authentic prophetic word; the prophetesses' hand binds and exploits. The recognition formula applied to the prophetesses: even they will know who YHWH is when their authority is broken.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Because with lies you have discouraged the righteous person, whom I had not grieved, and you have encouraged the wicked person not to turn from his evil way so as to preserve his life' — the social harm of false prophecy: it inverts the moral order. The righteous (<em>tzaddik</em>) are discouraged (their integrity is undermined); the wicked (<em>rasha</em>) are emboldened (told their lifestyle is acceptable). This inversion of the prophet's proper function (comfort to the afflicted, affliction to the comfortable) is the core crime of false prophecy in its social dimension.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Therefore you shall no longer see false visions or practice divination; I will deliver my people from your hands' — the cessation of the false prophets' authority is itself an act of deliverance. The community's liberation from false spiritual guidance is simultaneously the judgment of the false guides. The chapter closes with the recognition formula: 'then you will know that I am the LORD' — even the false prophetesses will be brought to acknowledge the LORD whose name they were using.</p>"
  },
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>The scene: elders of Israel came to Ezekiel and sat before him — the posture of disciples sitting before a teacher or clients before an oracle. In the ancient Near East, consulting a prophet was a formalized social activity: the petitioner came with a question, sat before the prophet, and waited for a divine answer. These elders represent the leadership of the exilic community in Babylon and their desire for YHWH's guidance on their situation.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The word-event formula introduces YHWH's unexpected response — not the oracle the elders expected, but an exposure of their spiritual state. The consultation framework is interrupted before it can begin. YHWH's response is to the prophet, not yet to the elders: the divine speech diagnoses the situation before addressing the petitioners.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'These men have set up their idols in their hearts and placed the stumbling block of their iniquity before their faces' — <em>gillulim</em> (H1544, idols — literally 'dung-balls,' Ezekiel's derogatory term) set up within the heart (<em>lev</em>). The 'idols in the heart' are not necessarily physical cult objects but interior devotions, loyalties, and spiritual commitments that compete with YHWH. In the exilic context, these may include Babylonian deities (Marduk, Bel, Nebo) adopted alongside YHWH-worship in a syncretistic accommodation to Babylonian religious culture. 'Should I be consulted by them at all?' — YHWH refuses the consultation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Any man of the house of Israel who sets up his idols in his heart and yet comes to a prophet — I the LORD will answer him according to the multitude of his idols' — the frightening divine principle: YHWH will give an answer that corresponds to what the petitioner actually worships. If the person's heart is full of idols, the divine answer will address the idol-worshipper — a response calibrated to the idolatry, not to the stated question. This is the principle of judicial hardening: YHWH answers according to the heart's actual orientation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'This is to lay hold of the house of Israel in their own hearts — for they have all become estranged from me through their idols' — the 'laying hold' (<em>taphas</em>, H8610, seize/capture) of Israel through their own hearts is the mechanism of judicial accountability. The idols that Israel has adopted become the means by which YHWH holds them accountable: they will be answered according to their actual devotion, not their professed devotion. The estrangement (<em>zur</em>, H2114, to be a stranger/be estranged) from YHWH through idols is the spiritual situation that makes the consultation impossible.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Therefore say to the house of Israel: Repent and turn away from your idols; and turn your faces away from all your abominations' — the repeated <em>shuv</em> (turn/repent) is the prophetic invitation within the judgment oracle. Even the oracle that refuses consultation ends with a call to repentance. The consultation itself is not condemned; the idolatry that makes authentic consultation impossible is condemned. The path forward is <em>teshuva</em> — turning away from the idols, turning toward YHWH.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'For any man of the house of Israel, or any foreigner (<em>ger</em>) who lives in Israel, who separates himself from me and sets up his idols in his heart' — the principle applies to resident aliens as well as native Israelites. The theological universalism: YHWH's demand for exclusive devotion applies to all who dwell in his covenant space, not only to ethnic Israelites. The inclusion of the <em>ger</em> in the oracle of judgment (and by implication in the restoration promises) is consistent with Ezekiel's broader theological concern for the integrity of the covenant community.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'I will set my face against that man, make him a sign and a byword, and cut him off from the midst of my people; then you will know that I am the LORD' — the three escalating responses: (1) <em>sim panim be</em> (set face against) — divine opposition; (2) <em>shem le'ot ulimeshalim</em> (become a sign and proverb) — public humiliation as a cautionary example; (3) <em>karat miqerev ami</em> (cut off from the midst of my people) — excommunication. The cutting-off from the community is the covenant-curse sanction for deliberate covenant violation (Lev 20:1-5).</p>",
    "9": "<p>'And if a prophet is deceived and speaks a word, I the LORD have deceived that prophet' — the principle of divine judicial hardening applied to false prophecy. YHWH's sovereign deceit of false prophets is the OT theology of the lying spirit (1 Kgs 22:19-23: a spirit comes before YHWH, volunteers to be a lying spirit in the mouth of Ahab's prophets, and YHWH sends it). The prophet who speaks for idolaters receives a divinely distorted oracle — the mirror of what they deserve. Both the false prophet and the inquiring idolater receive 'I will stretch out my hand against him.'</p>",
    "10": "<p>'They shall bear the consequences of their iniquity — the punishment of the prophet and the punishment of the inquirer shall be alike' — the equal accountability of the false prophet (who speaks what he has not been told) and the idolatrous inquirer (who consults with an adulterous heart). The communal nature of false prophecy: both parties to the false consultation bear guilt. The false prophet who accommodates the inquirer's idolatry shares the inquirer's judgment.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'This is so that the house of Israel may no longer wander away from me, nor defile themselves with all their transgressions, but that they may be my people and I may be their God' — the telos of the judgment is covenantal restoration. The harsh oracle about idolaters and false prophets serves the same end as the restoration promises: the reconstitution of the covenant relationship. The divine refusal of false consultation, the judicial hardening, the equal punishment of prophet and inquirer — all serve this one purpose: that YHWH might be Israel's God and Israel might be his people (the covenant formula again).</p>",
    "12": "<p>New oracle unit introducing the most abstract section of chs 11-14: the four-judgments/three-righteous-men teaching. The theological problem addressed: in what circumstances can individual righteousness save a community? The oracle systematically works through each of the four covenant-curse judgments and applies the Noah-Daniel-Job test to each.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'When a land sins against me by acting in grievous faithlessness (<em>ma'al ma'al</em>), I will stretch out my hand against it and break its staff of bread and send famine upon it' — <em>ma'al</em> (H4604, unfaithfulness/breach of covenant/treachery) — the strongest term for covenant violation in the Hebrew vocabulary. The 'staff of bread' (<em>matteh-lechem</em>) broken — the agricultural abundance that supported life removed as covenant curse (Lev 26:26: 'I will break your staff of bread'). The first judgment: famine.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Even if these three men — Noah, Daniel, and Job — were in it, they would deliver only their own lives by their righteousness' — the three paradigmatic righteous men of the ancient world: Noah (who survived the flood's universal judgment); Daniel (likely the ancient hero Dan'el of the Ugaritic Aqhat epic, known for his justice toward orphans and widows, not the biblical Daniel who was Ezekiel's contemporary); Job (the paradigm of righteousness tested and vindicated in suffering). All three are known for surviving extreme judgment or maintaining righteousness in crisis — but none could save others by their righteousness alone.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Second judgment scenario: wild beasts that depopulate the land so that no one passes through because of the animals — the covenant curse of Lev 26:22 ('I will let loose wild beasts against you, which shall bereave you of your children, destroy your livestock, make you few in number, so that your roads shall be deserted'). The four curses in this section (famine, wild beasts, sword, plague) correspond exactly to the four threats listed in Lev 26:21-33 and are the standard formula for covenant-curse judgment throughout the OT.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Though these three men were in it, as I live, declares the Lord GOD, they would deliver neither sons nor daughters; they alone would be delivered, but the land would be desolate' — the 'as I live' oath formula (<em>chai ani</em>) is YHWH's most solemn guarantee: on his own life he swears. The point is blunt: even the three most righteous men known to tradition cannot intercede successfully for a land determined to be judged. Individual righteousness is transferable only within limits — it cannot save sons and daughters from the consequences of a land's comprehensive covenantal unfaithfulness.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Third judgment: the sword. The formula is structural and somewhat mechanical — the same outcome (only the three righteous men themselves saved, no sons or daughters) is repeated for each of the four curses. The repetition is rhetorical: the exhaustive application to all four forms of judgment drives home the impossibility of intercessory salvation for a doomed land.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The third application of the Noah-Daniel-Job test: even with sword as the instrument, the three righteous men could not save others. The theological argument builds through repetition: no matter which instrument of divine judgment — famine, beasts, sword, plague — the result of the test is the same. Individual righteousness cannot avert comprehensive national judgment. The contrast with Abraham's intercession for Sodom (Gen 18:22-33) is implicit: Abraham sought to save Sodom if ten righteous could be found, but even three supremely righteous men cannot save a land that YHWH has determined to judge.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Fourth judgment: plague (pestilence, <em>dever</em>, H1698), the most comprehensive of the four — poured out with fury (<em>chemah</em>, H2534) in bloodshed (<em>dam</em>). The blood-judgment connects to the blood-guilt that pervades the Jerusalem oracles (chs 16, 22-23). Plague and blood together represent the judgment of a city polluted by innocent blood, which by ancient covenant logic (Num 35:33) required expiation either through the blood of the guilty or through the exile/destruction of the community.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The fourth and final application: even Noah, Daniel, and Job could not save sons or daughters — only their own lives. The repetition of 'as I live' strengthens the rhetorical force as the section reaches its climax. 'They would deliver neither sons nor daughters' — the specific reference to sons and daughters suggests that the intercession of the righteous might naturally be expected to protect their family. Even this natural expectation is denied in the comprehensive judgment scenario. The righteous escape personally; their families do not automatically share their righteousness.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'How much more when I send my four devastating judgments upon Jerusalem — sword, famine, wild beasts, and plague' — the argument from lesser to greater: if even one of the four curses (each individually) cannot be averted by the righteous men, how much more devastating is the simultaneous application of all four? The four judgments against Jerusalem are not sequential or alternative but cumulative. The historical evidence: Jerusalem experienced exactly this combination — Babylonian sword, siege famine, the abandonment of livestock and devastation of the city, and the epidemic that accompanied ancient sieges.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Yet behold — there will be a remnant left in it who will be brought out, sons and daughters; they will come to you and when you see their ways and their deeds, you will be comforted about the disaster I have brought upon Jerusalem' — the unexpected turn: a remnant will survive and come to the Babylonian exilic community. The survivors of Jerusalem's fall are not saved by righteousness but by YHWH's preserving purpose. Their function is testimonial: the exilic community will be 'comforted' (<em>nechamu</em>) not by the survivors' righteousness but by the evidence that YHWH acted justly.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'They will comfort you when you see their ways and their deeds, and you will know that I have not acted without cause in all that I have done to it' — the survivors' behavior when they arrive in Babylon will itself be the vindication of YHWH's justice. The exilic community, seeing the moral character of those who survived Jerusalem's fall, will understand why YHWH's judgment was necessary and just. The recogni<br>tion formula closes the chapter: 'you will know that I have not acted without cause' — the theodicy of the exile is confirmed not by argument but by evidence.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'ezekiel')
    merge_comm(existing, EZK_CTX)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'ezekiel', existing)

    out = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/commentary/mkt-context/ezekiel.json').read_text())
    il  = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/interlinear/ezekiel.json').read_text())

    all_ok = True
    for ch in [11, 12, 13, 14]:
        ck = str(ch)
        missing = set(il.get(ck, {}).keys()) - set(out.get(ck, {}).keys())
        if missing:
            print(f'ch {ch} STILL MISSING: {sorted(missing, key=int)}')
            all_ok = False
        else:
            print(f'ch {ch}: complete ({len(out.get(ck, {}))} verses)')
    if all_ok:
        print('All verses present')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
